neighborhood_overview:
West Hampstead is, to all intents and purposes, just one street - West End Lane. It is located in the London Borough of Camden, in zone two of the London Underground. It borders Belsize Park/Finchley Road to the east, and Kilburn/Willesden to the west. In the north are Cricklewood and Golders Green, whilst to the south lie uber-refined St. John's Wood and Maida Vale. The area is home to three train stations (all, confusingly, called West Hampstead!) and is a bona fide yuppie stronghold.
Though West Hampstead is hardly a place that springs to mind when you think nightlife, it has a smattering of good restaurants, pubs and bars. On the whole, the area's watering holes are towards the swankier (and pricier) end of the spectrum, and places tend to feel more mature feel than, say, Camden Town.

neighborhood_overview:
If you're looking for the best places to eat, drink, shop and explore in London, Hoxton and Shoreditch are the top choices! Hoxton is a vibrant and fiendly area in the London Borough of Hackney, situated just north of the City of London (financial district). It has a great community feel, with local pubs like the Howl at the Moon on Hoxton Street offering a welcoming atmosphere. Shoreditch and Hoxton are often confused as they have a historical link and were both part of the Metropolitan Borough of Shoreditch in the past. However, Hoxton is more residential than Shoreditch, making it an ideal place to live and mingle with locals.

The southern half of Hoxton is now a hub for arts and entertainment, with plenty of bars, nightclubs, restaurants, and art galleries to explore. The area centres around Hoxton Square, a beautiful park surrounded by former industrial buildings and the elegant 19th century parish church of St John's.
The trendy vibe of Hoxton and Shoreditch is

neighborhood_overview:
It is a quiet and peaceful neighbourhood with friendly and supportive neighbours around.

Northolt Leisure Centre is on Eastcote Lane North. It has a gym, two swimming pools, library and cafe.

There is an award winning chip shop called the Codfather, which is 10 minutes walk away, also a local restaurant from the Harvester chain called Mandeville Arms on the opposite side of Mandeville Road, which also serves breakfast. There is also a newly converted Wetherspoon Pub and Eaterie called The Greenwood also 10 minutes walk away.

Local shops and services such as supermarket, petrol station, chemist, bank, post office etc are situated at the end of the road called the Fairway, also along Mandeville/ Church Road beyond the station.

East of this main road along Ealing Road you can find a beautiful Listed Church surrounded by the attractive green spaces of Belvue Park. There is a friendly pub/ restaurant called The Crown.

neighborhood_overview:

15 minutes south is the delightful open spaces of London Fields surrounded by ancient plane trees, & with an outdoor heated Lido. Down the lovely green reaches of the River Lea, you can walk in the Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park and complex, Hackney and Walthamstow Marshes, or along the delightful Regent's canal bordering Victoria Park, one of the biggest parks in London.
host_about:
Film maker, musician, and traveller... 

I've lived in Hackney in east London for over 20 years, and I still delight in the area.  I would encourage anybody to visit this side of London…it's the alternative side, like Kruezberg in Berlin, Williamsburg in NYC, or Christiania in Copenhagen. There's elements of all of those in Hackney. 

I try and travel somewhere exotic once a year or so, ideally with a film-making purpose attached. 

I've been Airbnb'ing for over 10 years, I've met some amazing guests and think it's on the whole a fantastic and worthwhile community.

name: Boat in London · ★4.98 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
description:
This fascinating houseboat is 10 minutes' walk from the Tower of London.

The space
Thank you for your interest in our unique historic barge moored on the River Thames. Please message us to enquire about availability and if you have any questions about staying onboard before booking.

Staying aboard you will have exclusive use of the forward converted hold with open plan living / kitchen / diner, bedroom, bath & WC.

The living space has DVD player and stereo. WiFi is also included throughout the barge. The space is heated by a clean burning oil stove and supplementary electric radiators if needed.

The compact galley is stocked with complementary tea and coffee. There is a three burner gas hob, an excellent combination microwave and conventional oven, small electric kettle, toaster and refrigerator with a small freezer.

The separate bedroom has a king-size bed fitted with quality linens, a full length mirror and hair-dry
neighborhood_overview:
Wapping is one on London's hidden secret neighbourhood. Centrally located but with a village feel. Walking along the quiet cobbled street at dusk past the converted warehousing and historic buildings is a magic experience and then dipping into one of the historic pubs for a drink - heaven!

To the west is St Katherine Dock which by contrast is the gateway to the city with modern bars and restaurants to suit all budgets as tastes!
host_about:
Hi there  Paul here - my four favorite things are barges, the Thames, London and architecture. I am very lucky that I can enjoy all of these and can now share them with visitors via airbnb.

Four random selections from our collection aboard:
CDs: Bach Cantatas, Eva Cassidy, Gipsy Kings, Massive Attack
DVDs: Sunrise, When Harry Met Sally, Of Gods and Men, The Birds
Vinyl: Stevie Nicks, Jim Reeves, Purcell, Lalo
Books: Simon Raven, PG Woodhouse, Rem Koolhaus

A keen amateur cook, I look forward to welcoming guests with a few treats.
Travel for me is simple but comfortable - I take a lot of things with me to make life a little better (notorious for taking bentos on planes and refusing all provided in-flight food, much to delight of flight crew!).

My favourite place to stay is Therme Vals designed by Peter Zumthor. I try to make regular pilgrimages to this shrine of food, architecture and relaxation - perfect in every way!

I am passionate about sharing London and Maxime (our barge) with visitors and giving a unique insight into hidden London and life on the water.

Look forward to welcoming you aboard.

Paul

name: Home in Greater London · ★4.97 · 1 bedroom · 3 beds · 1 bath
description:
This lovely, artsy home is in a private road in Primrose Hill, just a few steps from trendy cafés & shops. It combines elegance, exclusivity, and a casual, relaxed vibe with all the quirky charm of an old, historic property. Right next to Regents Park, the Roundhouse (where the Apple Music Festival happens), Camden Market, London Zoo and perfect for art and culture lovers. Great for public transport. Bedroom, bathroom, kitchen, study, huge double-height living space - all for you!

The space
This exceptional home was historically an artist's studio, one of twelve houses specially built for British artists to live and work in, in the mid-19th century. Accessed through a private road and charming courtyard, the Primrose Hill Studios enclave is one of London’s hidden jewels, rich in cultural history. Many of Britain’s leading artists have lived here, including J.W. Waterhouse, Arthur Rackham, and – more recently – John Hoyland and Patrick Caulfield.

Once i
neighborhood_overview:
Primrose Hill is famed for its many residents in the arts and entertainment industry. It also attracts authors, academics, politicians, bankers, media professionals, and entrepreneurs who enjoy living in a fashionable, affluent and yet authentic, quiet and friendly urban village. We love the way it combines the very best that London has to offer.

Two minutes' walk from the house is a lovely park with views across the whole of London. Within a few minutes’ walk you will find London Zoo, Regent’s Park, the famous Camden Lock fashion market, canal walks and cruises, delightful shops, cafés, gastro-pubs and restaurants, jazz and other music venues, yoga classes and wellbeing treatments.

The many great restaurants include vegan and vegetarian, French cuisine, Greek, Italian, Indian, fusion and more.

The nearby parks offer elegant gardens, tennis courts, a fitness circuit, children’s playgrounds, summer concerts, an open air theatre, boating lakes and sport
host_about: I am a lifelong global traveller. I have experienced much kindness from others when travelling, and I enjoy providing an experience of relaxed, luxury travel to friends old and new.

The train line connects to Waterloo, Charing Cross and London Bridge so it is great for the Southbank, National Theatre, the West End and Covent Garden by train. At the end of my road are cafes, a great local pub and some handy shops. There is wi-fi throughout the flat.

The space

Guest access

neighborhood_overview:
Ladywell has a small village feel, with a popular cool pub and a couple of cafes at the end of the road (5mins walk). We also have a great deli, an independent butchers, a newsagents and some handy corner shops. If you need it there's a dry cleaners and a post office all at the end of the road. You can walk to Brockley in 20 mins for more restaurants and pubs.

The flat is on a 'no through road', so its very quiet and at the end of the road is a lovely park with tennis courts, a small river and I love to take a rug there to chill out.

Its about 15 mins walk to lewisham where there is a sports centre and swimming pool, a fruit & veg market, shopping centre and more train connections. Greenwich is a bus ride away (or a long walk through Greenwich park). The centre of London is an easy fast train hop away, and I like coming back to the quieter feel of Ladywell when I've been out.
host_about: I like to feel at home when I travel so I am excited about joining Airbnb as a way to see more of the world without feeling too much like a tourist and I'm hoping my flat can be the same for you. I've lived in London for over 20 years so I hope I can help you find what you want to explore in this city.

neighborhood_overview:
Many who choose to make their home here remain for decades, so the high street that dominates the area is not merely a great collection of boutiques, restaurants and cafes but also acts as a social hub. In fact, locals are so attached to their North West London enclave and its village vibe that they organise regular community meetings open to all. As a location flanked by Hampstead, Swiss Cottage and Kilburn, West Hampstead allows residents to borrow the best of their neighbours’ amenities. Hampstead Heath is a short walk away, as are the shops, cinemas and leisure complexes of Swiss Cottage and Finchley Road. The three train stations on West End Lane provide easy routes both across London and as far as Brighton.

Going out
Eating and Drinking: The Wet Fish Cafe is a local institution, both for its excellent food, popular music and arts events. Don’t leave without trying one of its delicious cocktails. Run by three local brothers, try David's Deli for delicious, Lebanese

neighborhood_overview: Crystal Palace is lively, friendly and fun and has a big beautiful park, perfect for kids (there are dinosaurs in there from the Victorian era!) and leisurely walks. There's a big lake, a farm, cafe and ice cream vans etc and it's all across the road from the flat. Wapping is a district in East London, England, in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets. It is situated between the north bank of the River Thames and the ancient thoroughfare simply called The Highway. Wapping's proximity to the river has given it a strong maritime character, which it retains through its riverside public houses and steps, such as the Captain Kidd, Town of Ramsgate, Prospect of Whitby and Wapping Stairs.

Famous London attractions including St Katharine Docks (an array of shops, cafe's, restaurants and bars can be found here), Tower Bridge and The Tower of London are just 7/8 minutes walk from the apartment.

neighborhood_overview:
Newington Green is a gift of an area, there is so much history and heritage here.

* The first record of the area is as 'Neutone' in the Domesday Survey of 1086.

* In the 16th century the area was connected to the court of Henry VIII. The king himself used a house on the south side of the Green as a base for hunting the wild bulls, stags and wild boars that roamed the surrounding forest.

* The area became the home of English Dissenters during the 17th century.

* And finally ... 52-55 Newington Green is London's oldest surviving brick terrace, dated 1658.

description:
Fantastic 4 Bedroom house in Crystal Palace (3 double beds, and 2 singles).
There's a large open plan living area and kitchen downstairs as well as an outside space and one downstairs bedroom. You'll find four more bedrooms upstairs.

Close to Crystal Palace's shops and restaurants, and in a lovely, quiet area within reach of central London.

I'll be away from the house, but not too far, so I can show you around. It'll be great to meet you!

The space
Large, Bright, modern house with garden bordering park. In easy reach of the restaurants and bars of Crystal Palace, and the football stadium.

Guest access
The garden and patio are open to guests and make a great place for a BBQ or a glass of wine. The garden backs onto a local woodland park, so it's regularly visited by squirrels, foxes, woodpeckers and surprisingly, even London's local parrots!

Come and relax.
neighborhood_overview:
Crystal Palace is a great area of London. The pubs, bars and restaurants of "the triangle" are just a few minutes walk away, and cater for all tastes. We're on the top of one of the biggest hills in London here, so there's a spectacular view of the city, or the surrounding area around every corner.

In addition, there are more local parks and green areas than almost anywhere in London. The biggest of these is Crystal Palace park - which features a national sports centre, the ruins of the Crystal Palace itself, a community farm, a maze, a boating lake, and the famous victorian dinosaur sculptures.

Just down the hill from us (7 minutes on the bus or a 20 minute walk) is the Crystal Palace football stadium, and a little further afield you'll find Dulwich (site of the world's oldest private art gallery), Croydon, Bromley, Sydenham, and Penge.
host_about:
I'm an animator and writer of children's books, so I work from an office in the garden, and I'm around most of the time.  I've been living in South East London for 20 years now, and have a fairly good idea of my way around the city.  

I'm fairly sociable, and I have two children so I'm aware of what's needed if you are travelling with kids.  

I look forward to meeting you.

neighborhood_overview: Fashionable Notting Hill is one of London's most iconic neighbourhoods. Best known as host to the world’s second biggest carnival (after Rio’s Mardi Gras) and home to the famous Portobello Road Market, Notting Hill is also a serious destination for culture buffs and those on the hunt for a quintessential London experience. On weekends throughout the year, crowds stroll the two-mile stretch of Portobello Road Market.  Colourful terraces are interspersed with antiques shops, buskers, historic pubs and clothing stalls.  Straddling the antiques and fashion markets (which are busiest on Saturdays) are the equally old-fashioned and charming produce markets, the calls of fruit and veg sellers helping give the place a Dickensian air. There’s street food of all kinds, from paella and bratwurst to crepes and churros. The markets have a grungier feel past the Westway sports centre, but it is worth persevering for the people-watching and to admire the 100m-long Portobello Wall, which features publ
host_about: Hi there! I’ve lived in a few countries but settled in London 12 years ago. Now got the travel bug again, so you can rarely catch me at home. Notting Hill remains my base camp, and it’s very hard to find somewhere else that would de-root me from this lovely area  - but I will keep trying! :)

Home truths:
host_about:
Greetings from the Veeve team!


Veeve manage the largest collection of homes to rent for short stays in London since 2011, launching in Paris in 2017. Our rental homes are predominantly privately-owned, lived-in homes in vibrant neighbourhoods. Thanks to our fully managed service, when you stay in a Veeve property you can benefit from the spaciousness, personal style and relaxed feel of a home – but with all the amenities of a hotel.


Once a booking is confirmed our Customer Service team will become your main point of contact and get in touch with you to organise your arrival at the property (including airport transfers, upon request); after which our on-the-ground management team will look after all aspects of your stay, with in-stay support available to help with any queries.


We have strict cleanliness guidelines for our cleaners and all staff who enter our properties and have reinforced existing cleaning procedures in line with official WHO, British and French government guidance.


As always, our team ensure that all properties are cleaned to a professional standard before and after each stay, with increased focus on touch-point cleaning (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.).

 All staff who enter properties will follow the below procedures:
 

- Carry and regularly use alcohol-based hand rub
- Sanitise their mobile phones 
- Focus extra attention when cleaning key touch-point areas (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.)
- Wear protective gear where appropriate
- Wash and disinfect work shoes


We might be able to arrange for property viewings, upon request, for stays of over 28 nights. 

Please be aware once a booking is confirmed you will be required to complete a Rental Agreement and also  ID verification via our partners Superhog. This is mandatory for all our stays and in accordance to short lets requirements with Veeve.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us and we will be sure to answer you promptly.

neighborhood_overview:
This is one of the most up-market residential locations in London, and is a lively yet safe area. There are many pubs and restaurants in the vicinity, and a good selection of local shops within only a few minutes’ walk in either direction from the front door, including a bakery, a supermarket with post office facilities, an organic shop, dry cleaners, hairdressers and an Everyman Independent Cinema.
Nearby is trendy Camden Market, Lords Cricket Ground, and the fresh air and stunning scenery of Hampstead Heath.
Swiss Cottage Leisure Centre with its 25m pool, well-equipped gym, yoga classes, climbing wall, sports hall, squash courts, outdoor football and full spa is 20 minutes walk away and open from 06.30 to 10 pm most days.
The Royal Free Hospital is under 10 minutes walk away.
host_about:

She often rents out the master bedroom in her flat to guests and shares the kitchen and dining room with them then; most of the reviews relate to that. Although friendly and sociable, she likes to have her own space; thus, she is  respectful of the need of others for privacy.  
Sometimes when she is away travelling she rents out the entire apartment, so those guests also get access to the large drawing room and will have the entire place to themselves.   
She is glad to advise about sightseeing in London and travel to other places in the UK, so please don’t hesitate to ask if you need help or guidance. 
As a guest she aims to be respectful, clean and tidy.
Her passions include reading, studying history, hiking in nature and yoga.

host_about:
Greetings from the Veeve team!


Veeve manage the largest collection of homes to rent for short stays in London since 2011, launching in Paris in 2017. Our rental homes are predominantly privately-owned, lived-in homes in vibrant neighbourhoods. Thanks to our fully managed service, when you stay in a Veeve property you can benefit from the spaciousness, personal style and relaxed feel of a home – but with all the amenities of a hotel.


Once a booking is confirmed our Customer Service team will become your main point of contact and get in touch with you to organise your arrival at the property (including airport transfers, upon request); after which our on-the-ground management team will look after all aspects of your stay, with in-stay support available to help with any queries.


We have strict cleanliness guidelines for our cleaners and all staff who enter our properties and have reinforced existing cleaning procedures in line with official WHO, British and French government guidance.


As always, our team ensure that all properties are cleaned to a professional standard before and after each stay, with increased focus on touch-point cleaning (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.).

 All staff who enter properties will follow the below procedures:
 

- Carry and regularly use alcohol-based hand rub
- Sanitise their mobile phones 
- Focus extra attention when cleaning key touch-point areas (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.)
- Wear protective gear where appropriate
- Wash and disinfect work shoes


We might be able to arrange for property viewings, upon request, for stays of over 28 nights. 

Please be aware once a booking is confirmed you will be required to complete a Rental Agreement and also  ID verification via our partners Superhog. This is mandatory for all our stays and in accordance to short lets requirements with Veeve.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us and we will be sure to answer you promptly.

You are also right by Shoreditch and Broadway Market where there is an ample amount of bars and restaurants, so you will never run out of places to go.

neighborhood_overview:
Talfourd Rd is a tree-lined street that runs from one of South London’s busiest roads at the bottom, to views over central London and a beautiful neighbourhood park at the top. The apartment, although far away from the traffic noise, is only a 2 minute walk from a 24 hour supermarket and Peckham Pelican cocktail bar and pizzaria in one direction, and South London gallery’s restaurant and café in the other. At the top of the street is Warwick Gardens, a small city park with a children's playground and plenty of trees to sit under and relax.

You will love the apartment's location! Within 10-15 minutes walk are 3 inner London neighbourhoods, each with their own distinct styles. Camberwell is residential, with great local eateries like Angels & Gypsies and FM Mangal, and a great cocktail bar called The Grand Union. Bellenden is a gentrified foodie haven with Andersons, The Begging Bowl, Artusi, and Ganapati.

Peckham itself combines an inner city location and eas
host_about:
We are a couple from New Zealand (Steve) and England (Laura), living in London.  We love exploring 'off the beaten track' places, but now that we are starting a family, are probably moving more toward exploring cities and taking in culture and food.

We have really enjoyed using Airbnb as guests, and love the feeling of being in a local neighborhood when visiting foreign cities.  We love the effort Airbnb hosts make to welcome their guests and give them local knowledge, and we look forward to providing the same to guests visiting our amazing city of London.  Our favourite destinations have been Colombia, Vietnam, and Albania.

We live in Peckham, an inner city London neighborhood.  We love how it combines its own  unique buzz with amazing transport links to the whole of London.  Since we moved here 6 years ago, Peckham has morphed from a gritty working class neighbourhood to a creative hub, with a constant stream of new eateries, pop-ups, and exhibitions.  The heart of this community is Franks, a bar on the top of a multistory car park, now an open air exhibition centre, which attracts throngs from across the city to drink cheap cocktails while enjoying the incredible views over the whole city.

Peckham Rye itself retains a lot of it’s grit, with international food stores and cafes interspersed with Hipster bars and pizzarias.  Move a couple of blocks closer to our flat and you find Belenden Rd, a gentrified foodie haven with an ever increasing array of independent restaurants that regularly feature in London’s best places to eat.

For us, the best things about living in London are the culture (Laura) and the architecture and bakeries (Steve).  We love the touristy things in London, but we also have a great knowledge of London's secrets, and we will be happy to give you tips and ideas whether it is food, art, history, music, or anything else you are looking to find.

neighborhood_overview:
I have so much to say about Surbiton, which I *love*. It is a mixed, middle-class neighbourhood- some people have lived here forever and others are new families who have immigrated to London from around the world. neighborhood_overview: The house is on the popular Progress estate. Built in 1915 for the workers in the arms factory in Woolwich (WW1), each house has a different lay out while keeping a uniform characteristic white wash, cottage like appearance from the front. Owners take great care of the outside aspect of their houses because it is a conservation area. The estate is very quiet, like living in a village with easy access to both the city and the countryside. We have shops and amenities 2 minutes from the house and are also a 10 minute walk to Eltham village High street which has everything one needs, supermarkets, banks, all sorts of shops and an English language school. The gym is a 5 minute walk and tennis and golf clubs are a short bus ride. Eltham palace is a beautiful historical place to visit as are the Plesaunce Park and Tudor barn.

I listen and dance! Having lived in italy for many years we live quite a mediterranean life style, especially where food is concerned. I ran a B and B in Rome and loved making breakfasts for my guests. Breakfast here in London is an optional extra.
We often host young people or students coming from abroad who stay with us for a few months while they find their feet in London! As a parent of three I am accustomed to helping young people find their way and always try to be supportive. My sons (aged 15 and 18) often have friends around so it is easy for guests to socialise with other young people. 
We also sometimes host guests on a weekend visits to London and try to be helpful about how to travel around, what's on in London etc.

A short distance away, Brockley market is a nice way to spend a Saturday morning trying out local food and produce and the Brockley Brewery is a quirky little space where they brew their own beers on site.

host_about: Hi, I'm Jade & I've grown up in London. I live with my husband Stuart in SE London where we bought our then not so nice house and converted it into a home we both love. We have different interests but the same tastes and share a common love of good food and travel. I think this city is pretty special and has so much to offer... great art, music, independent stores, great coffee shops, and exceptional restaurants. It's immersed in history and culture and has plenty of open green spaces within the hustle and bustle of the city. If it's your first stay I hope you get a small glimpse of what London is about and that your stay is enjoyable and memorable.

neighborhood_overview:
Famous for its maritime history as well as being the home of time, Greenwich is a picturesque area situated on the banks of the River Thames with plenty of cafes, restaurants and bars, as well as the large expanse of Greenwich Park and The Wilderness Deer Park to explore. Many would consider Greenwich to be one of the most historically rich neighbourhoods of London, with the area dominated by the grand Old Royal Naval College and, further up the hill, the Royal Observatory which sits on the meridian line (the point from which all time zones are calculated around the world). The maritime heritage of the area is summed up in the presence of the beautiful Cutty Sark - an imposing old clipper ship used to speed tea from Asia to Victorian Britain - which is open to the public throughout the year. You can also visit the National Maritime Museum, located in the grounds of the Naval College, for a taste of Britain’s nautical history.

The closest grocery store is Pravins Supermarket

neighborhood_overview:
Stoke Newington is a vibrant yet relaxed area - one of London's nicest, most interesting neighborhoods. It has the feel of a village (albeit a very 'hip' one) where the character is carefully protected from the growing samey-ness of most British high streets. All of the shops (with one exception - 'Whole Foods') are independently run by people who care about what they do.
There's a fantastic green grocers, where you can get virtually anything you could imagine. There's a top notch baker and butcher along with newsagents, coffee shops, restaurants and pretty much anything else you're likely to want or need.
You'll be right beside Clissold Park (a lovely public park, with duck ponds, deer and an aviary) and close to Dalston, Shoreditch, Islington and Liverpool Street.

PS: Daniel Defoe (Robinson Crusoe) and Edgar Allen Poe both went to school on Stoke Newington Church Street, although not at the same time...

After a busy day exploring London, retreat to an oasis of calm in this modernised, chic Victorian house with a mix of modern and antique styles and lots of natural light. Gaze up at the stars under the skylights.

This is one of three different rooms we have just specially converted for Airbnb in our newly renovated grand Victorian house in the wonderful enclave of Crouch End. The room is light and spacious and all newly furnished with a king size bed with Tempur Pedic mattress and a private ensuite bathroom. You will love it because it has all been architect-designed with high ceilings, flooded with light and great access to Crouch End and Finsbury Park.

There is underfloor heating throughout the house, and your bathroom has heated mirrors to avoid misting up, as well as a heated towel rail and Hansgrohe shower.
We have been very successfully hosting Airbnb guests in our former house over the last year - please see reviews by clicking on me as the host!
neighborhood_overview: Crouch End is a wonderful mix of urban and rural London, with the feel of a safe and cool village, yet only four miles from the city centre. There are a multitude of independent shops, cafes, restaurants, pubs, and cinemas five minutes away on foot.
host_about:
I am a yogi!  I teach Iyengar yoga in my studio in the garden as well as organising yoga holidays in Turkey, Alpujarras, Greece, Costa Rica and Kenya!   I live by my motto which is Carpe Diem! I love standing on my head, hiking, different cultures, entertaining, and cooking. I value independence and challenges, so these guide my holiday choices. I also love meeting new people!

In a former life i was marketing professional working for WPP.

name: Home in London · ★5.0 · 4 bedrooms · 3 beds · 2.5 baths
description:
A stylish, London townhouse in the heart of trendy Islington. Perfect for families & work stays, or as a base for exploring everything that London has to offer. The townhouse has a warm & homely feel in the middle of bustling London, with a lovely, south-facing, private garden.

We want to make your stay as comfortable as possible, so we provide two changes of The White Company linen for each bed, towels, essentials (e.g. hairdryers, soap), and a welcome hamper filled with English goodies!

The space
The townhouse is spread over 5 floors in the classic Georgian townhouse style. Though it has been refurbished & redecorated recently, the house retains several period features, (including marble fireplaces, wooden flooring, shutters & coal vaults). It is a listed building, which means it has been accorded historical & cultural significance by English Heritage.

Guest access
You'll have the house & garden all to yourself. There is no ac
neighborhood_overview:
The first thing to say about Barnsbury is the wealth of brilliant pubs! From the old-fashioned Victorian bars at the Drapers Arms (independently owned) and the Crown, to the Albion (a rowdy, weekend boozer with a huge garden), to the excellent food at the Pig & Butcher, there are some brilliant places to while away the hours.

There are some great cafes such as Sunday, or, closer to Angel, the coffee houses on Camden Passage. Islington also has a strong tradition in theatre, with many award-winning productions at the Almeida, and a thriving am-dram scene at the King's Head and the Red Lion.

There are plenty of trendy restaurants on Upper Street in Islington, including Ottolenghi, Oldroyd, Frederick's (a personal favourite of ours), Oldryods, and Rok.

Highbury Fields, Regent's Park, and Hampstead Heath are not too far, and there are lovely walks both east and west along the Regent's Canal from Angel.
host_about: Currently based in London. Between us, we've lived in Paris, New York Cambridge and Bath, and we’ve used Airbnb for stays all over: from Dublin to Dehli and Bristol to Bombay! We've been hosting guests at Barnsbury Corner since December 2018.

Private room in spacious period family house in friendly residential road right by Brockwell Park, with its 5km running path, walled garden, ponds, cafe.

Sunny, quiet, single room, where guests say they get a really good sleep! Perfect for everyone from solo women to business travellers. Shower room with walk-in power shower.

The space
Surrounded by eclectic art and decor from my travels - lighting from Italy, furniture from France, objets from India, kilims from Turkey - everyone remarks on the originality and individuality of my home. Being just a few steps from the park makes it a very special corner of a lovely neighbourhood in London.

neighborhood_overview:
Herne Hill is a hip, laid-back area to live, attracting young professionals and creative people. We love the Herne Hill Farmers Market 10am-4pm every Sunday, 10 minutes walk through the park. We are one minute from the entrance to Brockwell Park, with its Lido (huge outdoor swimming pool), tennis courts, membership gym, 5km running circuit and cafe. Our park is very special, with a historic house on a hill in the centre, surrounded by landscaped grounds with mature trees and meadowlands, and ponds with a resident heron and many ducks and geese.

In October there is the Herne Hill Music Festival, with gigs in lovely spaces including churches and the park greenhouse.

Head the other way to Brixton and in 10 minutes you're in one of the most happening neighbourhoods in London, with the vibrant covered market, which in the evenings turns into Brixton Village, a maze of boutique restaurants and bars. Hackney is also known as 'Hipster Hackney' - along with Shoreditch it has been one of THE up and coming neighborhoods in the East of the city for the last few years. It was for many years one of London's poorest boroughs and has a diverse range of people from all over the world living within its borders. In the last few years, house prices have rocketed and it's now the home of writers, pop stars, artists, photographers, stylists and florists and any other creative niche you can think of. Food, drink, and bars, are great here, as is nightlife and special interest evenings of all sorts. Cycling to and from the city is popular and an edgy community spirit remains.

Nearby attractions include the Broadway Market the music hall Hackney Empire, and the London Fields Brewery, as well as green spaces like London Fields park, and Victoria Park.

host_about:
I'm a 43 year old woman, who works in the film/TV/environmental sector and I love to travel and find adventures. I'm pretty independent, and am quite happy looking after  myself, but then I'm always open to a party or invitation to have some fun with new friends. 

Things I can't live without (apparently this is what people want to read about)....a good book, my music, actually there's not much I can't live without but I do love sunshine and scenery, mooching around antiques shops, discoveries, dive bars, dancing, animals, horseriding, live music (especially jazz and blues), a good debate, laughing (amazing, that!) and plenty more besides. 

Favourite travel destinations have included Cuba (for the music, definitely not the food!), Rome for the history, Ibiza for the parties and vibe, Argentina and Ecuador for the scenery and vastness and wildlife....and on and on.

As a guest, I am respectful, tidy, quiet and a non smoker.

neighborhood_overview:
The Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea is one of the most desirable and exclusive areas in London and for good reason. You are in the centre of town, with easy access to all major city areas (and tourist attractions), yet the area retains a village-like quality and there is plenty of green to make you forget the busy city life. Kensington and Chelsea is also home to some of the best restaurants and bars in London, built to cater for the affluent locals who enjoy artisan foods and quality wines and cocktails.

The area is famed for it's 'yummy mummies' and 'ladies that lunch' and you'll spot some of London biggest movers and shakers as well as the traditional Chelsea crowds within the many local cafes, bars and restaurants that surround the area.

South Kensington is also famous for its boutique shopping while Sloan Square has the famous Peter Jones John Lewis store as well as some of the most well known designer brands in fashion.

neighborhood_overview: The trendy and creative hub of Shoreditch hosts the best places to eat, drink and visit all within walking distance. Shoreditch accommodates some of London’s most cutting edge eateries and with culinary delights to suit all budgets. Check out Brick Lane, which continues to be a mecca for curry fans from all over the city and is a great way to spend an afternoon wandering around the vintage shops, trying the delicious street food and looking at street art. If you like shopping we recommend a trip to Blitz London - hailed as the biggest vintage shop in Europe! There is also the famous BoxPark here which is a little shopping area made from old shipping containers - great for shopping, eating and enjoying a drink in the evening! Additionally, make sure to take a trip to Columbia Road flower market on a Sunday, where this outdoor market is a great place to spend the morning strolling through the flower-adorned streets. neighborhood_overview: Shoreditch is a trendy and creative hub that offers a variety of options for eating, drinking, and visiting, all within walking distance. From cutting-edge eateries to street food, there are culinary delights to suit all budgets. A must-visit spot is Brick Lane, which is famous for its curry and vintage shops. Blitz London, the biggest vintage shop in Europe, is also worth checking out if you're into shopping. For a unique shopping and dining experience, head to BoxPark, a shopping area made from old shipping containers. On Sundays, don't miss the Columbia Road flower market, a great place to stroll through the flower-adorned streets. For a night out, catch a movie at the Rooftop Film Club at Queen of Hoxton, an outdoor cinema with a killer view. Screenings tend to fill up fast, so it's best to book in advance.

neighborhood_overview:
The house is in the Queens Road area of Peckham. The little park outside has a children's playground, an outdoor gym and some sports areas.

There is a wonderful cafe at the end of the road that seems to be always open and does really great food and coffee and pizza in the evening. There are a few more great places along this stretch.

Peckham 'Central' is about a 1 mile away (15-20 mins walk, 5 min cycle or about 2 mins on the train), where famous Franks Bar, Bellenden Village, Bussey Building, galleries, a huge selection of interesting bars and amazing food etc. can be found.

Camberwell is about a mile in the other direction with more great bars, pubs, restaurants etc.

New Cross is about a mile in the other direction with more great bars, pubs, restaurants etc.

There is the most wonderful selection of food everywhere.

Brixton is enjoying an undeniable renaissance, which has added to what was already a vibrant, multi-cultured, urban hub.

Brixton has its own unique vibe - it was where some of the first West Indian immigrants settled in London and since then has seen arrivals from Latin America, Eastern Europe and Africa. It is a melting pot of cultures and cuisines and famous for it market and sound systems. It has become a 'destination' for Londoners and those from further afield, and it the perfect place to experience a unique area of London or travel in to see the sites.

There are numerous restaurants and bars in the renowned Brixton Village as well as the recently opened Pop Brixton that are well worth checking out. Both are minutes from the house. Brixton Market is a bustling market boasting a wide range of traders from fruit and veg to arts and crafts and independent boutiques. Brixton Academy is one of London's best music venues and attracts top lineups, and there are a nu

name: Townhouse in London · ★4.87 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
description:
Recently renovated Victorian Terraced Home, two bedrooms, open plan kitchen dining room with bifold doors onto the garden, and walk in dressing room and master bathroom. Inhabited by two adorable and friendly cats! Retains lots of its original charm but with added colour. Situated in a quiet street in Bermondsey, just over a 10 minute walk to tube and lots of buses nearby for easy access to central London. Area is known for its weekend food markets and excellent local restaurants.

The space
The whole house will be completely yours during your stay. There’s a very large living room with sofa, armchair and television for when you want to relax, and a newly installed open plan kitchen and dining room for cooking, eating and looking out into the garden. And when the weather is good, you can open the bi-folding patio doors and spill out onto the patio and garden. Upstairs you’ll find two double bedrooms and a large walk-in wardrobe / dressing room onto the master bath
neighborhood_overview: Bermondsey was voted the best place to live 2018 by the Sunday Times, saying it "reflects the rise of an area that epitomises the modern urban good life.” I couldn’t agree more! The area is full of local food markets, independent bars, award-winning restaurants and galleries. Maltby Street Market and Bermondsey Street - both a short walk away - are must do’s, as is Bermondsey’s famous beer mile of independent breweries. The area is also very well connected making it easy to explore the rest of London.
host_about:
Hi I’m Alex, a rare actual London born and bred! I’ve been living in Bermondsey for about 9 years now and adore it, mainly for the incredible array of local markets and really good quality local independent restaurants.

I love travelling and try to visit a few new places each year; in November I'm off to trek the Sahara. In my spare time I can be found reading (1000+ books in my house and counting) doing yoga, drinking lots of home made green juices, much to the disgust of my colleagues, visiting one of London's many art galleries, sober raving in the morning and listening to opera at the Royal Opera House. I also love to escape to the English Countryside and the South of France on a regular basis. 

I renovated my lovely Victorian terraced home about a year ago to amongst other things add a new kitchen, complete with American fridge/freeze, a walk in dressing room and walk in shower, and an open plan kitchen dining room onto the garden. It’s also very bright! But I’ve kept some of the original touches like the exposed brick fireplace. It’s also home to two very adorable cats who will need feeding whilst you stay! 

I can give great tips on local attractions and London as a whole. I hope you enjoy my home as much as I do! :)

host_about:
Hi! Hello! Salut! Hola! Ciao! Ni Hao! Привет!

My name is Roman, before UK I used to live in US, Hungary, Slovakia and Ukraine.  I am an Engineer by education, Chef by passion and Entrepreneur by spirit.  I was engaged in a number of projects across different fields of interest, and I've lived in London since 2015.  Living here is very challenging but also very rewarding in many ways.  London is an amazing city and I want all the guests to experience the diverse beat and spirit that London has to offer. 

I enjoy traveling a lot but I enjoy hosting even more.  I like everything that is part of a peer-to-peer sharing economy.  Empty rooms, parked cars, unused tools, even dusty books, all of these can be made to work for other people and reward those whom it belongs to. 

So I'm helping people I know or have been recommended to in running their properties when they're away or busy with other things.  I enjoy engaging with travelers, answering questions, and providing some local info and advice. 

My other interests include cooking, hiking, kayaking, cycling and motorcycling, with lots of trips by foot, wheels and pedals already accomplished and many more to come.  Not to forget gardening and wild herbs and fungi foraging for my fusion recipes. 

I would be very happy to meet you in London and make sure that your stay is comfortable and enjoyable. 

Cheers!

We’re right in the heart of bustling central London, but just a short 10 minute stroll to the wide open spaces and pageantry of the Royal Parks - Hyde Park, Kensington Gardens and Palace.

In winter you are a short stroll from the UK's biggest Christmas market and fair - Winter Wonderland - with the UK’s largest outdoor ice skating rink, fair ground games and rides, an ice bar, an après ski-inspired ‘village’, loads of festive food stalls and German beer tents.

In Hyde Park you can also visit the Italian Gardens, go boating on the beautiful Serpentine lake or even riding at our local stables. If museums and galleries are more to your taste, it takes only 25-30 minutes walk south (or 10mins by cab) through Hyde Park to reach Exhibition Road where you will find The Science Museum, the Victoria and Albert Museum and The Natural History Museum. neighborhood_overview:
The area of Kensington is broadly defined. Its northern border is created by Holland Park Avenue. The southern border is a complex line where it meets Chelsea, both sharing similar architecture. The east of the borough has a green buffer through Kensington Gardens and Hyde Park with the West defined by the west London railway Line and Earl’s Court Road.
South Kensington boasts a sophisticated array of medium sized shops and boutiques alongside restaurants and bars. This area is easily accessible via the London Underground.

2 minutes from the Gloucester Road tube station, supermarkets just round the corner Waitrose, Sainsbury's, Tesco etc. The famous Hyde Park, Harrods, Royal Albert Hall, Victoria and Albert Museum, History Museum, Kensington Palace are only few of them, that's just 10 minutes walk from the property.
host_about:
I am a legal professional, with a number of international real estate projects. My general approach is professional, attentive and detailed. I strive to be efficient towards the goal of contributing best value.

My heart is invested in real charity. I co-run charitable endeavours in emerging countries that seek to build schools and hospitals, as well provide widows and orphans with vocational skills. I give consultative pro bono advice to London community libraries and the unrepresented. I channel my love of sport to run, cycle and row for MacMillan and St Luke's hospice. I believe best value is defined by empathy. I believe it is defined by serving the expressed need and preferences of the individual.   

My residential homes within the City of London are warmly and synonymously described “beautiful” and “comfortable,” a “home away from home” by most guests. You can be assured my attention to detail guarantees all photos are accurately represented. You will be able to see the modern and clean-cut features for yourself.

The central location of my homes assures your easy assimilation into all things culturally distinctive to London. You won’t miss a heartbeat; unless of course you are purely focussed on business or have become lost in love with the interior decor!  

My team and I are culturally diverse; speaking over 7 languages. We will be sensitive to your particular style. 

My apartments are optimised for corporate, family and individual stays.

We do look forward to serving you.

neighborhood_overview:
The famous Old Street is one of the many vibrant sections of Shoreditch, starting from Clerkenwell leading out to Shoreditch High Street. Shoreditch has become well known for its street art and designs which have established the area as the centre of the art world. Its location boasts excellent public transport links including Old Street station which provides easy access to the City and surrounding areas. Old Street is in close proximity of the City for workers and within walking distance to local bars and restaurants.

More information
Spitalfields Market, located on Horner Square, is a well-known local marketplace with more than 150 stalls each week. It's London’s oldest Victorian market hall open seven days a week and provides a combination of traditional and modern market stalls. For those searching for vintage fashion, homeware and unique jewellery designs, Spitalfields is the first destination.

description:
Welcome to our family home in South East London. We have a beautiful home with a wooded garden and tree house that can feel like a secret haven whilst being a short train ride into central London.

Brilliantly located between 4 train stations - each taking you directly into Central and East London and a short walk to bars, restaurants, parks and shops.

The space
Our house is often described as feeling like you are in the countryside despite being in London, largely due to the woodland garden that especially in summer can give the feeling of being very secluded.
James is both an artist and builder and has designed and built most of our home. As always doing this with a small child means we have done this in stages but we feel we have reached a point now where we can share the beauty of it with others.
My favourite feature is our kitchen
neighborhood_overview:
It is a very friendly area with local pubs and restaurants and also good parks for children. Some parks have views all over London. A short train will take you to Shoreditch or London Bridge/Waterloo for many central London attractions.
host_about:
Hello, my name is Liz and I live with my partner James and our son Ethan in South East London.   
I run my own business, a small boutique supporting independent artists and makers which doubles up as a yoga studio in the mornings and evenings. I love teaching yoga and meditation and sometimes get to teach in beautiful places outside of London.  I love our life here in London but also like to spend time in nature so we are looking forward to sharing our space when we are off travelling or just being in the countryside.

Sometimes we will rent out our spare room but in general we prefer to rent out the whole house when we are away. Our house is like a little haven in London with a big wooded garden so we hope you can find some chill out time here whilst in the city.

We look forward to sharing our space with you.  Liz

I am a legal professional, with a number of international real estate projects. My general approach is professional, attentive and detailed. I strive to be efficient towards the goal of contributing best value.

My heart is invested in real charity. I co-run charitable endeavours in emerging countries that seek to build schools and hospitals, as well provide widows and orphans with vocational skills. I give consultative pro bono advice to London community libraries and the unrepresented. I channel my love of sport to run, cycle and row for MacMillan and St Luke's hospice. I believe best value is defined by empathy. I believe it is defined by serving the expressed need and preferences of the individual.   

My residential homes within the City of London are warmly and synonymously described “beautiful” and “comfortable,” a “home away from home” by most guests. The central location of my homes assures your easy assimilation into all things culturally distinctive to London. You won’t miss a heartbeat; unless of course you are purely focussed on business or have become lost in love with the interior decor!  

My team and I are culturally diverse; speaking over 7 languages. We will be sensitive to your particular style. 

My apartments are optimised for corporate, family and individual stays.

We do look forward to serving you.

neighborhood_overview:
One of the world's most visited cities, London has something for everyone: from history and culture to fine food and good times.

Art & Culture
A tireless innovator of art and culture, London is a city of ideas and the imagination. Londoners have always been fiercely independent thinkers (and critics), but until not so long ago people were inherently suspicious of anything they considered avant-garde. That’s all in the past now, and the city’s creative milieu is streaked with left-field attitude, from theatrical innovation to contemporary art, pioneering music, writing and design. Food in all its permutations has become almost an obsession in certain circles.

Time Travel
London is immersed in history, with more than its share of mind-blowing antiquity and historic splendour. London’s buildings are eye-catching milestones in the city’s unique and compelling biography, and a great many of them – the Tower of London, Westminster Abbey, Big Ben – are familiar

neighborhood_overview: Just minutes away from Oxford Street but miles away in ambience, Marylebone is a surprising pocket of calm located in the very heart of London. Distinguished by leafy streets lined with stately period homes and stylish boutiques, it’s a true urban village complete with colourful local characters and a weekly farmers' market. Life centres on the busy high street, which positively brims with quaint cafes, unique independent stores and high end design retailers. The Conran Shop is a mecca for design enthusiasts, and Marylebone attracts a mixed bunch of celebrities, City professionals and well heeled young couples who live as well as shop here. Despite its fashionable profile, Marylebone is kept down to earth by its long term residents, friendly local shopkeepers and a strong community vibe. Cafes and restaurants spill on to pavements and you're unlikely to spend a day cafe hopping here without bumping into a friendly neighbour. It’s a bit of a foodie haven and there’s something for everyo

host_about:
Greetings from the Veeve team!


Veeve manage the largest collection of homes to rent for short stays in London since 2011, launching in Paris in 2017. Our rental homes are predominantly privately-owned, lived-in homes in vibrant neighbourhoods. Thanks to our fully managed service, when you stay in a Veeve property you can benefit from the spaciousness, personal style and relaxed feel of a home – but with all the amenities of a hotel.


Once a booking is confirmed our Customer Service team will become your main point of contact and get in touch with you to organise your arrival at the property (including airport transfers, upon request); after which our on-the-ground management team will look after all aspects of your stay, with in-stay support available to help with any queries.


We have strict cleanliness guidelines for our cleaners and all staff who enter our properties and have reinforced existing cleaning procedures in line with official WHO, British and French government guidance.


As always, our team ensure that all properties are cleaned to a professional standard before and after each stay, with increased focus on touch-point cleaning (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.).

 All staff who enter properties will follow the below procedures:
 

- Carry and regularly use alcohol-based hand rub
- Sanitise their mobile phones 
- Focus extra attention when cleaning key touch-point areas (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.)
- Wear protective gear where appropriate
- Wash and disinfect work shoes


We might be able to arrange for property viewings, upon request, for stays of over 28 nights. 

Please be aware once a booking is confirmed you will be required to complete a Rental Agreement and also  ID verification via our partners Superhog. This is mandatory for all our stays and in accordance to short lets requirements with Veeve.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us and we will be sure to answer you promptly.

neighborhood_overview:
In Shoreditch, empty walls are future murals. The neighborhood’s industrial warehouses and dingy side streets offer plenty of potential space waiting to be reimagined. Old brick warehouses have transformed into interactive art galleries, and countless buildings have served as Banksy’s canvases. Shoreditch’s appeal as a creative playground stems (at least, in part) from an urban, gritty underbelly, but clean-cut treasures aren’t in short supply—Shoreditch’s design sensibilities also influence its trendy pubs and cafes.

A triangle of influences have made Shoreditch into one of London’s most distinctive and unusual areas. To the East, Bangla-town and Brick Lane – London’s celebrated curry mile – are a riot of smells and colours from the Indian subcontinent. In the West, the looming towers of Liverpool Street and the City represent the world’s most concentrated area of money-making talent, where a number of sophisticated business hotels have sprung up. neighborhood_overview:
Highgate is a safe and great neighbourhood with an interesting mix of family houses and flats, brimming with beautiful architecture and green spaces. The house is a short stroll to the centre of Highgate Village, with its many quirky and unusual restaurants, charming gastropubs and cafes, as well as Pond Square, a lovely open space with trees and benches. The house itself is opposite the famous Highgate Cemetery - which you can visit at your leisure, or enjoy a guided tour to visit famous residents such as Karl Marx, Michael Faraday and George Eliot. Waterlow Park, a 26-acre "garden for the gardenless", (one of London's best kept secrets), a quiet oasis with ponds and views of London, has a mixed programme of events in the grounds at Lauderdale House.

The open-plan living/dining area and fully-fitted kitchen will make your stay a comfortable one. This apartment is equipped with complimentary linen, towels and toiletries.

The space
Our commitment is to offer an enjoyable stay which our guests will remember.
All apartments are handpicked by us for their great location and high quality interiors. From the moment you book to the moment you arrive, we are here to help you throughout the process so all you need to do is to make a list of places you would like to visit!
neighborhood_overview:
You will be spoilt for choice in the stylish area of South Kensington. The neighbourhood is full of world-class local cafes, restaurants and bars. There is a great shopping area on the iconic King's Road- Chelsea, the famous Harrods in Knightsbridge and the trendy boutiques of Kensington High Street.

If you fancy a bit of green space, take a stroll to Holland Park in just 9-minutes, Kensington Gardens in 15-minutes or a little bit longer for Hyde Park.

For culture, visit the world famous Natural History Museum, the Science Museum, the Royal Albert Hall and Victoria & Albert Museum. Alternatively, have a short ride on the tube and you will find yourself in the theatre land of the West End, afterwards walk to Buckingham Palace, The Houses of Parliament, Big Ben and The London Eye.

neighborhood_overview:
Bethnal Green is a strange place. It’s just in the edge of shoreditch which makes it quite edgy with a lot of graffiti, but also there can be a number of homeless people. I personally never feel unsafe here but it can feel quite intimidating if you grew up in the country.

What makes Bethnal Green great are all the pubs, the small alleys and interesting alcoves to get lost in. If you’re into fine dining I can also recommend some exquisite places that many people have never heard of. It’s still got a lot of the east London vibe without being overrun by non-Londoners.

Very happy to either show you around or recommend some places to you in London. We’re pretty knowledgeable about East London and can definitely help you get the most out of the city.

neighborhood_overview: This flat is just a 20-minute walk from Kensal Rise. Vogue once named Chamberlayne Road in Kensal Rise as “the hippest street in Europe” thanks to the shops, restaurants, bars and cafés located here and the beautiful trendy folk who frequent them. Few other places in the world get this sort of celebrity attention. Kensal Rise is in a prime location, sitting next to the City of Westminster and surrounded by areas including Notting Hill, Maida Vale, Paddington and Kensington. One of the main reasons why it’s such a popular area to stay in is the great transport links. Kensal Rise station provides connections through to Richmond and Clapham while Kensal Green tube station is on the Bakerloo line and a 20 minute journey from Oxford Circus. There are plenty of bus services and, for those feeling a little more athletic, there’s a bike path running along the canal from Kensal Rise to Paddington.

host_about:
Greetings from the Veeve team!


Veeve manage the largest collection of homes to rent for short stays in London since 2011, launching in Paris in 2017. Our rental homes are predominantly privately-owned, lived-in homes in vibrant neighbourhoods. Thanks to our fully managed service, when you stay in a Veeve property you can benefit from the spaciousness, personal style and relaxed feel of a home – but with all the amenities of a hotel.


Once a booking is confirmed our Customer Service team will become your main point of contact and get in touch with you to organise your arrival at the property (including airport transfers, upon request); after which our on-the-ground management team will look after all aspects of your stay, with in-stay support available to help with any queries.


We have strict cleanliness guidelines for our cleaners and all staff who enter our properties and have reinforced existing cleaning procedures in line with official WHO, British and French government guidance.


As always, our team ensure that all properties are cleaned to a professional standard before and after each stay, with increased focus on touch-point cleaning (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.).

 All staff who enter properties will follow the below procedures:
 

- Carry and regularly use alcohol-based hand rub
- Sanitise their mobile phones 
- Focus extra attention when cleaning key touch-point areas (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.)
- Wear protective gear where appropriate
- Wash and disinfect work shoes


We might be able to arrange for property viewings, upon request, for stays of over 28 nights. 

Please be aware once a booking is confirmed you will be required to complete a Rental Agreement and also  ID verification via our partners Superhog. This is mandatory for all our stays and in accordance to short lets requirements with Veeve.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us and we will be sure to answer you promptly.

neighborhood_overview:
Belgravia is regal London dressed in its Sunday best. Classical architecture, white stucco residences, and stone churches characterise the neighborhood’s fashionably restrained streets. Its aristocratic ambiance comes at a high price, but the neighborhood’s secluded gardens and private estates are unmatched. Although its daunting refinement places Belgravia in a class of its own, the neighbourhood remains close to destinations that encourage you to let loose—relax at Chelsea, Pimlico, and Westminster’s taverns and wine bars.

Exclusivity reigns in Knightsbridge, an epicentre of prestigious vocations and inimitable style. Its towering, columned edifices are home to renowned department stores like Harrods, couture fashion houses like Jimmy Choo, and banks that handle finances for the Queen. Perhaps there’s more to Knightsbridge than its posh digs and bevy of swanky, velvet-roped restaurants, but when a neighbourhood is as top-tier as this one is, no one seems to notice.

neighborhood_overview:
Traditionally a haunt for the London bohemia, Chelsea is now one of the city’s most affluent areas, with wide, elegant boulevards of period properties. Take a trip to King’s Road and Sloane Square and Avenue, the crown jewel of London haute-couture.

In times past it was also a haven to artists, scientists, and many other influential people. Chelsea was originally known as the “village of palaces” in the 17th Century, the only residents being those in palatial manor houses. Residents included Henry VIII, Sir Thomas More, Elizabeth I, the Duke of Monmouth and the Duke of Beaufort. On Embankment Gardens’ doorstep you’ll of course find the upscale Chelsea Embankment, with its wide view of the Thames and the elegant Ranelagh Gardens.

neighborhood_overview: A short stroll from Aldgate East tube station, The Gate is located at the gateway to the City and within a short walking distance of London’s most creative and vibrant areas of Shoreditch, Hoxton and Hackney, all alive with street art, independent restaurants and great bars. host_about:
The Gate is a boutique aparthotel launching in Aldgate East in March 2020. The 20 storey building comprises 189 rooms including studios and 1 and 2 bedroom apartments with City views. The Gate promises to combine a lifestyle hotel with apartment amenities to cater for a modern generation of long and short-term guests providing a Gateway to the capital. All rooms are equipped with fitted kitchens, Nespresso machines, Le Labo amenities and beautifully designed living areas. Public spaces are furnished with contemporary art from the renowned Maddox Gallery. The building houses Maple & The Gate, a brand new healthy café from Maple & Co., a 5th floor Members Lounge with bar and terrace and a gym fully equipped with Technogym equipment and Peloton bikes. 


Our Story
“The idea for The Gate and aparthotels was born out of traditional gate and guesthouses, where people would socialise in communal spaces then retreat to their private rooms. The gatehouses would often be right on the edge of a city, so guests could use the property as a base to easily explore the surrounding 
neighbourhoods. We wanted to recreate this offering and atmosphere for a modern audience. It’s really exciting to be launching our first aparthotel, introducing a new kind of hospitality experience to the London market - 
we cannot wait to see how our guests use the space.”

neighborhood_overview: There’s a reason why so many films are set in Notting Hill. The neighbourhood’s cobblestoned streets weave through scrunched alleyways and richly furnished Victorian town homes, and its stylish shops and passionate antique vendors satiate design-driven appetites—Notting Hill’s famed Portobello Road Market is a rummager’s delight. This flat is on the door step of a area in London near the heart of trendy Shoreditch & very close to Spitalfields market, Liverpool St station, Columbia Road Flower Market, Brick Lane, London Bridge, Shard and several other tourist attractions.
Shoreditch is one of the coolest neighbourhoods to explore if you are in London.
The area is thrumming with energy, or at least a lot of attractive young people walking from bar to cafe to boutique and back again.
The area has history of Artists and photographers occupying the studios vacated by the departing textile and tailoring businesses. In 1993, a group of Young British Artists, including Tracey Emin, Gavin Turk and Gillian Wearing, took part in a Fete Worse than Death in Shoreditch, in which they sold their wares on stalls, as though they were at a village fete.
Who would have predicted that the area would house a Versace shop, as there is now on Redchurch Street.

neighborhood_overview:
In Shoreditch, empty walls are future murals. The neighborhood’s industrial warehouses and side streets offer plenty of potential space waiting to be reimagined. Old brick warehouses have transformed into interactive art galleries, and countless buildings have served as Banksy’s canvases. Shoreditch’s appeal as a creative playground stems (at least, in part) from an urban, gritty underbelly, but clean-cut treasures aren’t in short supply—Shoreditch’s design sensibilities also influence its trendy pubs and cafes.

A triangle of influences have made Shoreditch into one of London’s most distinctive and unusual areas. To the East, Bangla-town and Brick Lane – London’s celebrated curry mile – are a riot of smells and colours from the Indian subcontinent. In the West, the looming towers of Liverpool Street and the City represent the world’s most concentrated area of money-making talent, where a number of sophisticated business hotels have sprung up. Rachel :)

neighborhood_overview:
Once an important part of London’s river trade, Bermondsey sat derelict for several decades, until the area’s wharves were renovated in the 1980s. Now it’s a lively part of town, with some exceptionally good restaurants and coffee houses, although they can sometimes be a bit tricky to find. Bermondsey also has plenty of excellent bars and pubs, usually packed to the brim with visitors and regulars. Bermondsey can turn Londoners into tourists: The Scoop in particular attracts both out-of-towners and locals to its free quality events.

If you haven’t already, make sure to take a stroll down Bermondsey Street to see what one of London’s most ancient streets has to offer. From the Bermondsey Street Festival to the Bermondsey Antiques Market, this street continues to thrive. I couldn’t recommend this area enough!

host_about:
Hi there! 

This part is always the most difficult to fill in, isn't it, so I'll just follow the guided format and share with you about 5 things I can't live without:
My God. My creditcard. My family and friends. Whatsapp. Travel 

I love going away for short breaks, anything more than 7days is too long for me.  New York is my favourite city break. If I could go to New York every weekend, I would. Lol
 
I am about to get married to my boyfriend of 10 years so it's excitement all around. We are having a destination wedding :-)
Update - 18/10/2014: We are now married!! Got hitched 07 Sep 2013. ;)

I love music, and tend to appreciate most genres. I think different music cater for different moods so when I'm melancholic then I love listening to Jazz, classical or soul.etc. 

I eat anything except red meat. This is not because of any religious or dietary obligations. I just do not have the taste for it.

I love travelling and have met with so much kindness along my travels. If I can just show back even just a fraction of the kindness that came my way to guests visiting our beautiful city, I think I'll die a very happy person! You can count on me for being a fabulous host and ensuring that I communicate well with you before, during and after your stay.

neighborhood_overview: Pimlico is an oasis in the centre of London. In between Victoria and Vauxhall, it is a quiet neighbourhood forgotten by time. With beautiful traditional architecture and an abundance of private garden squares, this furnished flat is in one of the most sought-after residential areas in the English capital. Walk around and you will find quaint shops, local high-quality restaurants and traditional pubs, all tucked away in hidden streets. In terms of transportation, you have Pimlico Underground on the Victoria Line within minutes away, offering easy connections into Central London. Westminster and Victoria Underground stations (District, Jubilee, Circle and Victoria lines) are also not far away and Victoria National Railway station has 30-minute connections into Gatwick airport, London’s second biggest Airport.
host_about:
We’re Blueground, a global proptech company with several thousand move-in-ready apartments in a growing number of major cities around the world. With flexible terms and homes in vibrant, centrally based neighborhoods, you’ll feel at home and free to roam for as long as you want — a month, a year, or longer. 

Each apartment is thoughtfully designed with exclusive furnishings, fully equipped kitchens, and incredible amenities – making every day a five-star experience. From day one, you’ll enjoy high-speed Wi-Fi, premium linens, and smart home entertainment. Plus, access to pools, gyms, and outdoor spaces in select buildings.

Why stress over your apartment? We provide a hassle-free alternative — a consistent, quality guest experience that starts even before you arrive. Because we let you book our most up-to-date apartment listings online, confirm with a click, pay securely, and check in easily. 

During your stay
Upon arrival, you’ll either be greeted personally by a Blueground team member or given self-check-in instructions. The entire apartment is yours! You’ll enjoy reliable support via email, phone, and our Guest App, where you can request everything from a home cleaning to extra towels. 

We’ll share all details upon confirmation of your stay.

host_about:
Greetings from the Veeve team!


Veeve manage the largest collection of homes to rent for short stays in London since 2011, launching in Paris in 2017. Our rental homes are predominantly privately-owned, lived-in homes in vibrant neighbourhoods. Thanks to our fully managed service, when you stay in a Veeve property you can benefit from the spaciousness, personal style and relaxed feel of a home – but with all the amenities of a hotel.


Once a booking is confirmed our Customer Service team will become your main point of contact and get in touch with you to organise your arrival at the property (including airport transfers, upon request); after which our on-the-ground management team will look after all aspects of your stay, with in-stay support available to help with any queries.


We have strict cleanliness guidelines for our cleaners and all staff who enter our properties and have reinforced existing cleaning procedures in line with official WHO, British and French government guidance.


As always, our team ensure that all properties are cleaned to a professional standard before and after each stay, with increased focus on touch-point cleaning (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.).

 All staff who enter properties will follow the below procedures:
 

- Carry and regularly use alcohol-based hand rub
- Sanitise their mobile phones 
- Focus extra attention when cleaning key touch-point areas (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.)
- Wear protective gear where appropriate
- Wash and disinfect work shoes


We might be able to arrange for property viewings, upon request, for stays of over 28 nights. 

Please be aware once a booking is confirmed you will be required to complete a Rental Agreement and also  ID verification via our partners Superhog. This is mandatory for all our stays and in accordance to short lets requirements with Veeve.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us and we will be sure to answer you promptly.

neighborhood_overview:
Battersea is a district of South West London which lies on the south bank of the River Thames. The area is particularly popular for young families and young professionals, attracted here by the proximity to central London, the cafe and restaurant culture and the shopping amenities.

Whether milling around Northcote Road Market or simply enjoying the green spaces, life in Battersea ticks along at a happy, upbeat pace.

Battersea Park, which is a day out in itself, with a children’s zoo, boating lake, mini golf, Go Ape, sports pitches and many acres of nature trails to explore on foot or on one of the recumbent bikes that can be hired for use in the park.

Battersea it's also the site of the world's most famous power station which is undergoing a massive transformation that will see it restored as home to Apple’s new London Campus.

host_about:
Greetings from the Veeve team!


Veeve manage the largest collection of homes to rent for short stays in London since 2011, launching in Paris in 2017. Our rental homes are predominantly privately-owned, lived-in homes in vibrant neighbourhoods. Thanks to our fully managed service, when you stay in a Veeve property you can benefit from the spaciousness, personal style and relaxed feel of a home – but with all the amenities of a hotel.


Once a booking is confirmed our Customer Service team will become your main point of contact and get in touch with you to organise your arrival at the property (including airport transfers, upon request); after which our on-the-ground management team will look after all aspects of your stay, with in-stay support available to help with any queries.


We have strict cleanliness guidelines for our cleaners and all staff who enter our properties and have reinforced existing cleaning procedures in line with official WHO, British and French government guidance.


As always, our team ensure that all properties are cleaned to a professional standard before and after each stay, with increased focus on touch-point cleaning (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.).

 All staff who enter properties will follow the below procedures:
 

- Carry and regularly use alcohol-based hand rub
- Sanitise their mobile phones 
- Focus extra attention when cleaning key touch-point areas (door handles, kitchen surfaces, kettles, taps etc.)
- Wear protective gear where appropriate
- Wash and disinfect work shoes


We might be able to arrange for property viewings, upon request, for stays of over 28 nights. 

Please be aware once a booking is confirmed you will be required to complete a Rental Agreement and also  ID verification via our partners Superhog. This is mandatory for all our stays and in accordance to short lets requirements with Veeve.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact us and we will be sure to answer you promptly.
